atha Christie's Poirot]]''\n|Nurse Hopkins\n|Episode: \"Sad Cypress\"\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Dalziel and Pascoe (TV series)|Dalziel and Pascoe]]''\n|Jenny Ettrick\n|Episode: \"A Game of Soldiers\"\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Murder in Suburbia]]''\n|Wendy\n|Episode: \"Noisy Neighbours\"\n|-\n|2004, 2010\n|''[[Silent Witness]]''\n|Helen Wharton, Jennifer Mears\n|Episodes: \"Death by Water: Parts 1 & 2\", \"Shadows: Parts 1 & 2\"\n|-\n|2005\n|''Beneath the Skin''\n|Grace Shilling\n|TV film\n|-\n|2005\u201306\n|''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]''\n|Diana Jewell\n|Episodes: \"4.8\", \"5.10\"\n|-\n|2006\n|''Missing''\n|Karen Foster\n|TV film\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Sea of Souls]]''\n|Elaine\n|Episode: \"Sleeper\"\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[Trial & Retribution]]''\n|Anna Wildsmith\n|Episodes: \"Curriculum Vitae: Parts 1 & 2\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Honest (TV series)|Honest]]''\n|Jenny\n|Episode: \"1.4\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Taggart]]''\n|Kathy Moffat\n|Episode: \"Trust\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[New Tricks]]''\n|Dr. Mathieson\n|Episode: \"Mad Dogs\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''{{sortname|The|Royal}}''\n|George Fawcett\n|Episode: \"Pastures New\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Wallander (UK TV series)|Wallander]]''\n|Inga Wallander\n|Episode: \"The Fifth Woman\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''{{sortname|A|Touch of Frost}}''\n|Christine Moorhead\n|Episodes: \"If Dogs Run Free: Parts 1 & 2\"\n|-\n|2010, 2012\n|''[[Lip Service (TV series)|Lip Service]]''\n|Judy\n|Episodes: \"1.4\", \"2.2\"\n|-\n|2010\u20132015\n|''[[Downton Abbey]]''\n|[[List of Downton Abbey characters#Mrs Hughes|Elsie May Carson]] (Mrs. Hughes)\n|Regular role\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Vera (TV series)|Vera]]''\n|Shirley\n|Episode: \"A Certain Samaritan\"\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''\n|Sandra Zins\n|Episode: \"The Lost Love in the Foreign Land\"\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|''{{sortname|The|Good Karma Hospital}}''\n|Maggie Smart\n|Main role (series 1), guest (series 2)\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Girlfriends (2018 TV series)|Girlfriends]]''\n|Linda Hutchinson\n|Main role\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Doctor Who]]''\n|Andinio\n|Episode: \"[[The Battle of Ranskoor Av Kolos]]\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n {| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n|1983\n|[[Taormina Film Fest]]\n|Golden Mask\n|''Another Time, Another Place''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|1984\n|[[Evening Standard British Film Awards]]\n|Best Actress\n|''Another Time, Another Place''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|1984\n|[[British Academy Film Awards]]\n|Best Actress\n|''Another Time, Another Place''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|1984\n|BAFTA Awards\n|Most Outstanding Newcomer to Film\n|''Another Time, Another Place''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|1986\n|[[David di Donatello|David di Donatello Awards]]\n|Best Foreign Actress\n|''Another Time, Another Place''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2013\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Downton Abbey''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2014\n|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Downton Abbey''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|2015\n|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Downton Abbey''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2016\n|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Downton Abbey''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2017\n|Screen Actors Guild Award\n|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Drama Series\n|''Downton Abbey''\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0517642}}\n\n{{Bafta Award for Most Promising Newcomer}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVDrama 2010\u20132019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Logan, Phyllis}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Paisley, Renfrewshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Conservatoire of Scotland]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:Scottish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Scottish television actresses]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:20th-century British actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century British actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Johnstone]]\n[[Category:Scottish radio actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actress}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Phyllis Logan\n| image        = Phyllis Logan May 2014 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size   =\n| caption      = Phyllis Logan at an event for ''Downton Abbey'' Cast and Creators, May 2014\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|01|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Paisley, Renfrewshire]], Scotland\n| alma_mater   = [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]] <small>(1977)</small>\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years active = 1977\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Kevin McNally]]|2011}}\n| children     = 1\n| residence    = [[Chiswick, London]], England\n}}\n'''Phyllis Logan''' (born 11 January 1956)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b9f2315ca |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |title=Phyllis Logan |accessdate=13 December 2016| archivedate= 14 December 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161214033901/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b9f2315ca| url-status=live}}</ref> is a Scottish actress, known for playing Lady Jane Felsham in ''[[Lovejoy]]'' (1986\u201393) and Mrs Hughes (later Carson) in ''[[Downton Abbey]]'' (2010\u201315). She won the [[BAFTA Award for Most Promising Newcomer to Leading Film Roles|BAFTA Award for Most Promising Newcomer]] for the 1983 film ''[[Another Time, Another Place (1983 film)|Another Time, Another Place]]''. Her other film appearances include ''[[Secrets & Lies (film)|Secrets & Lies]]'' (1996) and ''[[Shooting Fish]]'' (1997).\n\n==Education==\nLogan was born in [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]], [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-34808907| publisher=BBC News |title=10 reasons why Paisley is already a city of culture|date=13 November 2015|accessdate=13 December 2016| archivedate= 13 December 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161213051708/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-34808907| url-status=live}}</ref> and grew up in nearby [[Johnstone]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/14127286.Video_Downton_Abbey_star_from_Renfrewshire_takes_part_in_one_legged_wobble_challenge/?ref=arc |work=[[Evening Times]]| location =Glasgow |title=Video: Downton Abbey star from Refrewshire takes part in one-legged wobble challenge |date=6 December 2015|accessdate=13 December 2016| archivedate= 14 December 2016 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161214034118/http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/14127286.Video_Downton_Abbey_star_from_Renfrewshire_takes_part_in_one_legged_wobble_challenge/?ref=arc| url-status=live}}</ref> where she was educated at Johnstone High School.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/education/renfrewshire-council-1-1164504 |title=Renfrewshire Council \u2013 Education |work=[[The Scotsman]]|location=Scotland |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=13 February 2013| archivedate= 5 March 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160305075346/http://www.scotsman.com/news/education/renfrewshire-council-1-1164504| url-status=live}}</ref> She studied at the [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]] in Glasgow and graduated with the [[James Bridie]] gold medal in 1977.<ref>{{cite journal|title=My Scotland|journal=Scotland in Trust|page=23|oclc=49921348}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsusa.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Celebration-of-Scotlands-Treasures-Gala.pdf |publisher= [[The National Trust for Scotland Foundation USA]]|title=Celebration of Scotland's Treasures |accessdate=13 December 2016| archivedate=21 August 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160821192735/https://www.ntsusa.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Celebration-of-Scotlands-Treasures-Gala.pdf| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduation, she joined the [[Dundee Repertory Theatre]].<ref>{{cite press release| url=http://www.james-scott.com/about/press/film-reviews/shocking-accident-a/monthly-film-bulletin-4/press-release-2/ |title=Every Picture Tells a Story| publisher= [[James Scott (filmmaker)|James Scott]] official site| date= 20 December 1984| accessdate= 18 May 2015| archivedate= 4 March 2016| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060304/http://www.james-scott.com/about/press/film-reviews/shocking-accident-a/monthly-film-bulletin-4/press-release-2/}}</ref> She left in 1979 to work on stage in [[Edinburgh]]. She also worked regularly on Scottish television. On the BBC Scotland production, ''The White Bird Passes'', she first met writer-director [[Michael Radford]]. For his first feature film, ''[[Another Time, Another Place (1983 film)|Another Time, Another Place]]'' (1983), he cast Logan in the leading role of Janie, for which she won a Gold Award for Best Actress at the [[Taormina Film Festival]] and the [[Evening Standard Award]] for Best Actress in 1983 and the [[BAFTA]] Award for the Most Outstanding Newcomer to Film in 1984.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=scFAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=66UMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1873,116330&dq=phyllis+logan&hl=en | work=[[The Glasgow Herald]] | first= Ann| last= Shaw| title= Phyllis Logan Sets the Film World Buzzing|date= 1 August 1983|accessdate= 18 May 2015}}</ref> Before her success in ''[[Downton Abbey]]'', where she played the housekeeper [[List of Downton Abbey characters#Mrs Elsie Hughes|Mrs Hughes]], Logan was most identified with the role of Lady Jane Felsham, co-starring with Ian McShane for eight years in nearly 50 episodes of ''[[Lovejoy]]'', a comedy-drama for television.\n\nShe has also had a part in the 1996 [[Mike Leigh]] film ''[[Secrets & Lies (film)|Secrets & Lies]]''. Logan provided the broadcast voice of [[Ingsoc]] in a film version of ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four (1984 film)|Nineteen Eighty-Four]]'' (1984) and the [[Loch Ness Monster]] in the animated film ''[[Freddie as F.R.O.7]]'' (1992). She was in the radio series ''Coming Alive'' and ''[[Baggage (radio show)|Baggage]]''. She played Inspector Frost's love interest and eventual wife in ''If Dogs Run Free'', the last story in the ''[[A Touch of Frost]]'' series.\n\nShe played Maggie Smart in the '[[The Good Karma Hospital]]' (7 episodes, 2017-2018) on Acorn TV.\n\nShe played Andinio in \"[[The Battle of Ranskoor Av Kolos]]\", the tenth episode in the [[Doctor Who (series 11)|eleventh series]] of ''[[Doctor Who]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coming Soon, Series 11, Doctor Who \u2013 BBC One |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p06n75pt |website=BBC |accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLogan married actor [[Kevin McNally]] and has a son. The family live in [[Chiswick]].<ref name=express>{{cite news| first=Janie| last=Lawrence| url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/355083/I-ll-stay-in-Downton-Abbey-as-long-as-I-can-says-Phyllis-Logan| title=I'll stay in Downton Abbey as long as I can says Phyllis Logan| work=[[Daily Express]]| location=UK| date=29 October 2012| accessdate=14 March 2013| archivedate=28 August 2016| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6k6icpzkV?url=http://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/355083/I-ll-stay-in-Downton-Abbey-as-long-as-I-can-says-Phyllis-Logan| url-status=live| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n<!--DO ''not'' USE ROWSPANS PER WP:FILMOGRAPHY-->\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Another Time, Another Place (1983 film)|Another Time, Another Place]]''\n|Janie\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''Every Picture Tells a Story''\n|Agnes Scott\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''{{sortname|The|Chain|The Chain (1984 film)}}''\n|Alison\n|\n|-\n|1985\n|''{{sortname|The|Doctor and the Devils}}''\n|Elizabeth Rock\n|\n|-\n|1987\n|''{{sortname|The|Inquiry|The Inquiry (1986 film)}}''\n|Claudia Procula