{"title_page": "Babson College", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox university\n |name              = Babson College\n |native_name       = \n |image_name        = Babson College seal.svg\n | image_size      = 150px\n |caption           = \n |latin_name        = \n |motto             = \n |mottoeng          = \n |established       = September 3, 1919\n |closed            = \n |type              = [[Private university|Private]] \n |affiliation       = \n |endowment         = $459.4 million (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/offices-and-services/business-and-financial-services/|title=Babson College Financial Facts|first=Babson|last=College|website=www.babson.edu|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n |officer_in_charge = \n |chairman          = \n |chancellor        = \n |president         = Stephen Spinelli Jr. \n |vice-president    = \n |superintendent    = \n |provost           = Mark P. Rice\n |vice_chancellor   = \n |rector            = \n |principal         = \n |dean              = Ian Lapp (undergraduate)<br>Keith Rollag (graduate)\n |director          = \n |head_label        = \n |head              = \n |faculty           = 306 full-time\n |staff             = \n |students          = 3,113\n |undergrad         = 2,361\n |graduates        = \n |postgrad          = 830\n |doctoral          = \n |other             = \n |city              = [[Wellesley, Massachusetts|Wellesley]]\n |state             = [[Massachusetts]]\n |country           = United States\n |coor              = {{Coord|42|17|53.63|N|71|15|40.29|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n |campus            = [[Suburb]]an <br> {{convert|350|acre|km2}}\n |former_names      = Babson Institute<br />(1919\u20131969)\n |free_label        = \n |free              = \n |sports            = 22 varsity sports\n |colors            = [[Green]] and [[white]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Logo / Brand Usage \u2013 Quick Reference guide OCTOBER 2013|url=http://www.babson.edu/offices-services/marketing/guidelines-templates/Documents/babson-brand-guidelines.pdf|publisher=Babson College|accessdate=26 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413023946/http://www.babson.edu/offices-services/marketing/guidelines-templates/Documents/babson-brand-guidelines.pdf|archive-date=April 13, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><br>{{Color box|#006644|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n |nickname          = Beavers\n |mascot            = Biz E. Beaver\n |athletics         = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]]\n |website           = {{URL|http://www.babson.edu/}}\n |logo              = File:Babson College logo.svg\n |footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Babson College''' is a [[private school|private]] [[business school]] in [[Wellesley, Massachusetts]]. Established in 1919, its central focus is on [[entrepreneurship education]]. It was founded by [[Roger Babson|Roger W. Babson]] as an [[Men's colleges in the United States|all-male]] business institute but is now coeducational.\n\n== History ==\n\n===20th century===\n\n====The Babson Institute====\nOn September 3, 1919, with an enrollment of twenty-seven students, the Babson Institute held its first classes in the former home of Roger and Grace Babson on Abbott Road in Wellesley Hills.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} [[Roger Babson]], the founder of the school, set out to distinguish the '''Babson Institute''' from colleges offering mainly instruction in business. The Institute provided intensive training in the fundamentals of production, [[finance]] and distribution in just one academic year, rather than four. The curriculum was divided into four subject areas: practical [[economics]], [[financial management]], business psychology and personal efficiency (which covered topics such as ethics, personal hygiene and interpersonal relationships). The program's pace assumed that students would learn arts and sciences content elsewhere.\n\nBabson favored a combination of class work and actual business training. Seasoned businessmen made up the majority of the faculty. To better prepare students for the realities of the business world, the Institute's curriculum focused more on practical experience and less on lectures. Students worked on group projects and class presentations, observed manufacturing processes during field trips to area factories and businesses, met with managers and executives, and viewed industrial films on Saturday mornings.\n\nThe institute also maintained a business environment as part of the students' everyday life. The students, required to wear professional attire, kept regular business hours (8:30&nbsp;a.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m., Monday through Friday and 8:30&nbsp;a.m. to noon on Saturday) and were monitored by punching in and out on a time clock. They were also assigned an office desk equipped with a telephone, typewriter, adding machine, and Dictaphone. Personal secretaries typed the students' assignments and correspondence in an effort to accurately reflect the business world. Roger Babson aimed to \"prepare his students to enter their chosen careers as executives, not anonymous members of the work force.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.babson.edu/About/History.cfm |title=Babson College: History |work=babson.edu |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228002014/http://www3.babson.edu/About/History.cfm |archivedate=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, the Babson Institute's three-year bachelor of science in business administration, still for young men only, became a four-year bachelor of science degree, the Institute became a College and women were admitted for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babson.edu/about-babson/at-a-glance/babsons-history/timeline/Pages/default.aspx|title=Timeline \u2013 Babson History|first=Babson|last=College|website=www.babson.edu|accessdate=August 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826071426/http://www.babson.edu/about-babson/at-a-glance/babsons-history/timeline/Pages/default.aspx|archive-date=August 26, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n\n====Three College Collaboration====\nBabson is involved in a three college collaboration with [[Olin College]] and [[Wellesley College]] (a collaboration often referred to as BOW).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://centennial.babson.edu/babson100/|title=Babson 100|website=Babson Centennial|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bow3colleges.org/|title=Babson/Olin/Wellesley {{!}} Three College Collaboration|website=bow3colleges.org|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Wellesley Main Campus===\nThe main residential campus of Babson College is {{convert|350|acre|km2}} and located in the \"Babson Park\" section of [[Wellesley, Massachusetts]], just fifteen miles west of [[Boston]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babson.edu/About/ |title=About Babson |work=babson.edu |date=June 15, 2006 |accessdate=January 20, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101227181958/http://www3.babson.edu/About/| archivedate= December 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> It is adjacent to the [[Franklin W. Olin College of Engineering]]. Undergraduate and graduate students have the opportunity to take advantage of campus amenities including the student center, the cafeteria, Horn Library, multiple centers and institutes, the Webster fitness center, the Weissman Foundry the arts center, and a new centennial park known as the Kerry Murphy Healey Park. Executive and Enterprise Education visitors have the opportunity to stay in guest rooms adjacent to the meeting center.\n\n===Babson Boston===\nThe Babson Boston classroom and event space, located at 100 High Street, gives Babson a presence in downtown Boston and connects the resources of the College with the innovative companies, organizations and leaders in Boston's Financial District. Opened in 2016, this facility provides the opportunity to offer MBA courses in a location convenient to where entrepreneurial students live and work. Over the course of the academic year, there are opportunities at the Boston location for students to engage with Babson offices and resources, including graduate programs, the Graduate Center for Career Development, Graduate Admissions and the College's alumni network. From 2011 to 2016, Babson Boston campus was at 253 Summer Street in Boston's Innovation District.\n\n===Babson San Francisco===\nBabson has a San Francisco campus which includes a Blended Learning MBA program, an undergraduate semester experience and custom executive education.\n\n===Babson Miami===\nIn July 2017, President [[Kerry Healey]] announced Babson's plans to expand to [[Miami, Florida]], where the Blended Learning MBA, Master of Science in Business Analytics (MSBA) and Certificate in Advanced Management (CAM), three graduate programs are offered. Babson's new hub in Miami is located at 1200 Brickell Avenue.\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Undergraduate===\nBabson College offers all undergraduates a [[bachelor of science]] degree. Students are also given the option to declare concentrations their junior and senior year from a broad range of subjects in various business and other fields.  Programs are accredited by [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]] (AACSB)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://datadirect.aacsb.edu/public/profiles/profile.cfm?runReport=1&unitid=54394&userType=All |title=AACSB: Accredited institutions |work=datadirect.aacsb.edu |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref> and the College itself has been regionally accredited by the [[New England Association of Schools and Colleges]] (NEASC) since 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cihe.neasc.org/about_our_institutions/roster_of_institutions/details/8136|title=NEASC CIHE: Babson College|publisher=|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBabson College also offers a study abroad they have created. The program is called \"BRIC: The Cornerstone of the New Global Economy\" and is offered to Juniors as well as Seniors in the fall semester of the academic year. During the program a number of students, around 26, visit and study in Russia, China and India. In each country, students study a variety of classes covering different topics.\n\n{{Infobox business school rankings\n| BWu = 26\n| USNWRu =\n| BWg =56\n| FT = 60\n| USNWRg = 72\n| BI = 40\n}}\nIn rankings, Babson was rated first among all colleges and universities in the nation by ''[[Money Magazine]]'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/money/collection/moneys-best-colleges/ |title=The Best Colleges for Your Money |magazine=Money |year=2014}}</ref> In 2015, the magazine ranked it second just behind [[Stanford University]].<ref name=\"MONEY's Best Colleges\">{{Cite web|title = MONEY's Best Colleges|url = https://best-colleges.time.com/money/full-ranking#/list|website = best-colleges.time.com|accessdate = 2015-07-14}}</ref> Babson's MBA program has been ranked number one in [[entrepreneurship]] for twenty-one consecutive years by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Entrepreneurship \u2013 Best Business Schools|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-business-schools/entrepreneurship-rankings|accessdate=March 13, 2012|newspaper=U.S. News and World Report}}</ref> and is ranked 58th overall in the ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'' 2014 rankings.<ref>{{cite news|title=Full-Time MBA Programs|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bschools/rankings/|publisher=BloombergBusinessWeek|year=2014}}</ref> Babson's undergraduate business program is ranked 26th overall in the Bloomberg Businessweek 2014 rankings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bschools/rankings#5 |title=Undergraduate Business School Programs=Businessweek |year=2014 |accessdate=21 August 2015 |work=Bloomberg}}</ref> Babson's undergraduate Entrepreneurship program has been ranked number one for the past 17 years by ''U.S. News & World Report.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/rankings/business-entrepreneurship |title=College Ranking Lists > Entrepreneurship Rankings |publisher=U.S. News & World Report : Colleges |date=2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> In their 2013\u20132014 salary report, [[Payscale.com]] ranked Babson College at number five of all U.S. colleges and universities, ahead of schools such as Stanford, University of Pennsylvania, Harvard, Dartmouth, Columbia and Yale. This ranking represents an average mid-career salary of $123,000 and average starting salary of $59,700.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payscale.com/college-salary-report-2014/full-list-of-schools |title=Full List of Schools \u2013 PayScale College Salary Report 2013\u201314 |publisher=Payscale |date=2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112174459/http://www.payscale.com/college-salary-report-2014/full-list-of-schools |archive-date=November 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2012, ''Bloomberg Businessweek'' ranked Babson eleventh among U.S. schools based on return on investment. Babson is the highest ranking private business college. The others are either major universities or engineering schools.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-09/college-roi-what-we-found |first=Louis |last=Lavelle |title=College ROI: What We Found |magazine=Businessweek |date=9 April 2012 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> CNN money ranked Babson eighth in their 2016 \"Colleges with the highest-paid grads\" rankings.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://money.cnn.com/2016/09/20/pf/college/top-colleges-graduate-earnings/index.html | work=CNN | first=Katie | last=Lobosco | title=Colleges with the highest-paid graduates | date=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Graduate===\n\nBabson College offers master's degrees through its F. W. Olin Graduate School of Business, including a One-Year MBA Program, a Two-Year MBA Program, a 42-month Evening MBA Program and a Blended Learning MBA Program with campuses located in [[Boston]], [[San Francisco]] and [[Miami]]. It also offers a Master's of Science in Entrepreneurial Leadership (MSEL), Business Analytics (MSBA), Finance (MSF) and a Certificate of Advanced Management (CAM).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babson.edu/admission/graduate/Pages/default.aspx |title=Graduate Business Masters Degrees |publisher=Babson College |date=2016 |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n[[File:Arthur M. Blank Center, Babson College - IMG 0388.JPG|thumb|right|Arthur M. Blank Center]]\n[[Image:Babsonglobe2008.jpg|thumb|right|The Babson Globe]]\nIn 2019, 3,663 students attended Babson, 3,229 of whom were [[undergraduate]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/babson-college-2121 |title=Babson College |publisher=U.S. News & World Report : Colleges |date=2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nStudent publications include a literary magazine<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.babson.edu/Students/Undergraduate/Organizations/litmag/default.cfm/ |title='&#39;Babson Literary Magazine'&#39; |work=babson.edu |date=June 15, 2006 |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718150356/http://www3.babson.edu/Students/Undergraduate/Organizations/litmag/default.cfm |archive-date=July 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and the Babson Built Podcast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.babson.edu/entrepreneurship/2018/04/05/babson-built-podcast/ |title='&#39;Babson Built Podcast'&#39; |work=babson.edu |date=April 15, 2018 |accessdate=October 27, 2019 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are several [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|fraternities and sororities]] on campus: [[Chi Omega]], [[Delta Tau Delta]], [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]], [[Sigma Kappa]] and [[Sigma Phi Epsilon]]. There are also two professional business fraternities on campus: [[Delta Sigma Pi]] and [[Alpha Kappa Psi]]. Babson College Radio was started in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cybertalk.com/030198.htm |title=www.cybertalk.com |date=March 1, 1998 |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708214753/http://www.cybertalk.com/030198.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBabson offers a variety of special interest housing, such as CODE (Community of Developers and Entrepreneurs), theStudio (the housing associated with CREATE, the arts-based student club), E-Tower, ONE Tower: Origins of Necessary Equality, GIVE Tower, Healthy Living Tower and Women Giving Back Tower.\n\n==Athletics==\nBabson's teams are known as the \"Beavers\" and its colors are green and white. The school has 22 [[Varsity team|varsity sports teams]], the majority of which compete in the [[New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference]] (NEWMAC) of the [[NCAA Division III]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newmaconline.com/ |title=NEWMAC online |publisher=NEWMAC online |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208190434/http://www.newmaconline.com/ |archivedate=February 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> One of Babson's flagship sports is baseball which has won 7 Conference Championships and been to 5 NCAA Tournaments, including the 2019 College World Series. Additionally, the men's soccer team has established a history of success with 3 NCAA National Championships, 27 NCAA tournaments wins and 12 conference championships. The men's and women's alpine ski teams compete in the [[United States Collegiate Ski and Snowboard Association]] (USCSA)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uscsa.com/member-schools.html |title=Members |publisher=USCSA |accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> and the men's lacrosse team competes in the [[Pilgrim League]]. Babson College's men's hockey team competes in the [[Eastern College Athletic Conference]] (ECAC) and has won (1) NCAA D3 National title, (1) ECAC D2 title, six ECAC East Championships, appearing in the championship game in 9 of the last 12 seasons {{as of|2015|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babsonathletics.com/sports/m-hockey/2014-15/releases/20150305uwatxs |title=CAC East Championship Preview: No. 10/12 Men's Ice Hockey at No. 1/2 Norwich |publisher=Babson Athletics |date= |accessdate=21 August 2015}}</ref> Babson College's golf team competes in the [[New England Collegiate Conference]] (NECC) and won the title in 2011 giving them an automatic bid to the NCAAs. They were led by senior captain Joe Young who won NECC golfer of the year in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babsonathletics.com/sports/m-golf/index |title=Babson Athletics |publisher=Babson Athletics |date= |accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref> Babson United Rugby Club won Northeast region of NSCRO 7's in 2016. In 2017, the school will begin construction of the Babson Recreation and Athletics Center, a major new facility that will support varsity, intramural and recreational sports and many other activities by the fall of 2019. In March 2017, Babson's basketball team won the Division III National Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theswellesleyreport.com/2017/07/babson-has-huge-recreational-facility-overhaul-on-tap/|title=Babson has huge athletics/recreation facility overhaul on tap \u2013 The Swellesley Report - News about Wellesley, Massachusetts|website=theswellesleyreport.com|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni==\n{{Alumni|date=December 2016}}\n<!-- ONLY ADD A NAME TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE A WIKIPEDIA ARTICLE-->\n\n===Business and athletics===\n* [[Ernesto Bertarelli]] '89: Swiss businessman\n* [[Arthur Blank|Arthur M. Blank]] '63 H'98: co-founder, former CEO of [[The Home Depot]]\n* [[Peter Boss]] MBA '10: race car driver\n* [[Edward Bronfman|Edward Maurice Bronfman]] '50 (1927\u20132005): businessman, founder of [[Edper Investments]]\n* [[Matt Chatham]] MBA '11: former NFL linebacker with the [[New England Patriots]]\n* [[Anthony Chiasson]] '95: hedge fund manager\n* [[Matt Coffin]] '90: founder and former President of [[LowerMyBills.com]]<ref>[http://www.babson.edu/Academics/centers/blank-center/alumni-entrepreneur-hall-of-fame/Pages/2009-Honorees.aspx \"2009 Honorees, Arthur M. Blank Center for Entrepreneurship\"], Babson.edu. Retrieved October 31, 2013</ref>\n* [[Andr\u00f3nico Luksic Craig]] '76: businessman\n* [[Bob Davis (businessman)|Bob Davis]] MBA '85: founder and CEO of [[Lycos]]\n* [[Edsel Ford II|Edsel Bryant Ford II]] '73 H'00: Board Director of the [[Ford Motor Company]]\n* [[William D. Green]] '76 MBA '77 H'07: Former Chairman and CEO of [[Accenture]]\n* [[Frederic C. Hamilton]] '48 H'98 MP'82 (1927\u20132016): oil pioneer\n* [[Peter Kellogg|Peter R. Kellogg]] '64: financial broker\n* [[Will Langhorne]] '95: former race car driver\n* [[Peter E. Madden]] '64 P'04 Honorary Trustee: former President of the [[State Street Corporation]]\n* [[Dean Metropoulos|Charles Dean Metropoulos]] '67 MBA '68: co-owner of [[Hostess Brands]] and former owner of [[Pabst Brewing Company]] \n* [[Geoff Molson|Geoffrey Eric Molson]] MBA '96: co-owner, President and CEO of the [[Montreal Canadiens]]\n* [[David G. Mugar]] '62: businessperson\n* [[Gunnar S. Overstrom Jr.]] '65 (1942\u20132001): former Vice Chairman of [[FleetBoston Financial]]\n* [[Aly Raisman]] Olympic gold medalist for [[United States women's national gymnastics team]]\n* [[Scott Sharp]] '90: race car driver\n* [[Jamie Siminoff]] '99: businessperson\n* [[Jacob Sprague]] '07: rugby player\n* [[Akio Toyoda]] MBA '82 MP' 14: President and CEO of [[Toyota Motor Corporation]]\n\n===Food and entertainment===\n* [[Marc Bell (entrepreneur)|Marc Bell]] '89: entrepreneur\n* [[Terrell Braly]] '77: founder of [[Quiznos]]\n* [[Gustavo Cisneros]] '68 H'19: President/CEO of [[Grupo Cisneros|Organizacion Diego Cisneros]]\n* [[Roger Enrico]] '65 H'86 (1994\u20132016): former CEO of [[PepsiCo]] and [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] Animation SKG <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.referenceforbusiness.com/biography/A-E/Enrico-Roger-1944.html |title=Roger Enrico 1944\u2014 Biography \u2013 Two early lessons, Enters the cola wars, Turns attention to foods and restaurants |publisher=Referenceforbusiness.com |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Stephen Gaghan]] '88: screenwriter\n* [[Daniel Frank Gerber]] '20 H'67 (1898\u20131974): founder of [[Gerber Products Company]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hbs.edu/leadership/20th-century-leaders/Pages/details.aspx?profile=daniel_f_gerber_jr |title=Great American Business Leaders of the 20th Century |publisher=Harvard Business School |date=January 19, 2018 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Bernard Lee (poker player)|Bernard Lee]] MBA '99: professional poker player<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2012/11/the-busiest-man-in-poker |title=The Busiest Man in Poker |magazine=Harvard Magazine |date=November\u2013December 2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[John LeFevre]] '01: former Citibank banker\n* [[Mir Ibrahim Rahman]] '00: CEO of [[GEO TV]]<ref>http://www.geo.tv/anniversary/1st/english/page4.htm  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040412225608/http://www.geo.tv/anniversary/1st/english/page4.htm |date=April 12, 2004 }}</ref>\n*[[Nelson Woss]] '91: Australian film producer of ''[[Ned Kelly (2003 film)|Ned Kelly]]'' & ''[[Red Dog (film)|Red Dog]]''\n{{colend}}\n\n===Government, education, and other===\n* [[Craig Benson|Craig Robert Benson]] '77, businessperson, former Governor of New Hampshire\n* [[Vincent E. Boles]] MBA '88: Major General US Army \n* [[W. Haydon Burns]] '34 (1912\u20131987): 35th [[Governor of Florida]], 1965\u201367 and 35th Mayor of [[Jacksonville, Florida]], 1949\u20131965<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dos.myflorida.com/florida-facts/florida-history/florida-governors/william-haydon-burns/ |title=William Haydon Burns |publisher=Florida Department of State |date=|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Princess Marie of Denmark]]: attended 1995-97<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-royal-house/prince-joachim-and-princess-marie/hrh-princess-marie |title=HRH Princess Marie |publisher=The Danish Monarchy |date=|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Rudy Crew]] '72 H'96: President of [[Medgar Evers College]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/25/education/new-leader-is-named-for-medgar-evers-college.html |title=New Leader Is Named for Medgar Evers College |newspaper=New York Times |date=June 24, 2013 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Kathleen M. Gainey]] MBA '89: lieutenant general US Army<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.army.mil/article/8022/gainey_confirmed_by_senate_for_third_star |title=Gainey confirmed by Senate for third star |publisher=U.S. Army News Release |date=March 20, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[James A. Lewis]] '58 (1932\u20131997): American politician\n* [[Patricia E. McQuistion]] MBA '88: lieutenant general US Army<ref>{{cite news|url=http://qconline.com/news/local/first-female-senior-commander-returns-to-arsenal-for-women-s/article_ada0a4e3-c0b7-53c9-9465-859f56573442.html |title=First female senior commander returns to Arsenal for Women's Equality Day speech |publisher=The Dispatch\u2013Argus |date=September 4, 2016 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lafayette Morgan]] '58 (1931\u20132005): former Economic Advisor of Liberia<ref>{{cite news |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200504290902.html |title=Liberia: Former Economic Advisor in Liberia, Lafayette Morgan Dies At 74 |publisher=Liberian Observer |date=April 29, 2005 |accessdate=February 8, 2018 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20121013204409/http://allafrica.com/stories/200504290902.html |archivedate=October 13, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Ernest Dichmann Peek]] '29 (1878\u20131950): major general, U.S. Army\n* [[Gustavo Adolfo Carvajal Sinisterra]] MBA '84: the 24th Ambassador of Colombia to France<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com.co/economia/ocde-traera-grandes-oportunidades-embajador-de-colombia-en-francia.html |title=Ocde traer\u00e1 grandes oportunidades embajador de Colombia en Francia |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |date=June 2, 2013 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Don Strauch]] '49 (1926\u20132016): former Mayor of [[Mesa, Arizona]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/mesa/contributor/2016/02/04/mesa-history-remembering-mayor-don-strauch/79446386/ |title=Mesa history: Remembering Mayor Don Strauch |publisher=AZCentral USA Today |date=February 4, 2016 |accessdate=February 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Tilton]] (1951\u20132017) '74 P'09: art dealer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/10/arts/design/jack-tilton-dead-manhattan-gallery-owner.html|title=Jack Tilton, Art Dealer With an Eye for the New, Dies at 66|first=William|last=Grimes|date=May 10, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=August 31, 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Fashion and fitness===\n* [[Michael Bastian]] '87: founder of American menswear firm MICHAEL BASTIAN whose majority stake was acquired in 2016 by brand management firm Bluestar Alliance LLC whose annual brand retail sales exceed $3 billion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bluestaralliance.com/bluestar-alliance-buys-majority-stake-in-michael-bastian/ |title=Bluestar Alliance Buys Majority Stake in Michael Bastian |publisher=Bluestar Alliance |date=January 7, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/media/babson/site-assets/content-assets/about/events/babson-magazine/summer-2011/winter-2011/Feature-Fashion.pdf |title=They Got the Look |publisher=Babson College |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Enrico Marone Cinzano|Count Enrico Marone Cinzano]] '85: artist, furniture designer<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/yjeanmundelsalle/2016/06/13/italian-designer-enrico-marone-cinzano-creates-furniture-with-a-conscience/ |title=Italian Designer Enrico Marone Cinzano Creates Furniture With A Conscience |magazine=Forbes Magazine |date=June 13, 2016 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> and member of Italy's prominent [[Cinzano]] liquor family<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-10-31-mn-5-story.html|title=Count Alberto Marone Cinzano; Chairman of Vermouth Firm |publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=October 31, 1989|access-date=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ruthie Davis]] MBA '93: founder, President and designer of the fashion and footwear firm RUTHIE DAVIS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/about/entrepreneurs-of-all-kinds/profiles/ruthie-davis.php |title=Profiles Ruthie Davis MBA'93 |publisher=Babson College |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ruthiedavis.com/about/ |title=About Ruthie Davis |publisher=Ruthie Davis |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Natasha Esch]] '93: former President of [[Wilhelmina Models]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/03/10/a-successful-pose/33199152-d69e-4cd0-b139-961685fd6671/ |title=A Successful Pose |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 1993 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Mohan Murjani]] '67: as Chairman of the Murjani Group Murjani developed, launched and built [[Tommy Hilfiger (company)]] as well as [[Gloria Vanderbilt]] fashion empires<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/26/style/26iht-luxury08-Murjani.18176690.html |title=Mohan Murjani, chairman, Murjani Group |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 26, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Alberto Perlman]] '98: co-founder of Zumba Fitness\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Babson College}}\n* [http://www.babson.edu/ Official website]\n* [http://www.babsonathletics.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{New England Hockey Conference}}\n{{New England Collegiate Conference}}\n{{AICUM}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Babson College|*]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Wellesley, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Norfolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:New England Hockey Conference teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox university\n |name              = Babson College\n |native_name       = \n |image_name        = Babson College seal.svg\n | image_size      = 150px\n |caption           = \n |latin_name        = \n |motto             = \n |mottoeng          = \n |established       = September 3, 1919\n |closed            = \n |type              = [[Private university|Private]] \n |affiliation       = \n |endowment         = $459.4 million (2019)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/offices-and-services/business-and-financial-services/|title=Babson College Financial Facts|first=Babson|last=College|website=www.babson.edu|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n |officer_in_charge = \n |chairman          = \n |chancellor        = \n |president         = Stephen Spinelli Jr. \n |vice-president    = \n |superintendent    = \n |provost           = Mark P. Rice\n |vice_chancellor   = \n |rector            = \n |principal         = \n |dean              = Ian Lapp (undergraduate)<br>Keith Rollag (graduate)\n |director          = \n |head_label        = \n |head              = \n |faculty           = 306 full-time\n |staff             = \n |students          = 3,113\n |undergrad         = 2,361\n |graduates        = \n |postgrad          = 830\n |doctoral          = \n |other             = \n |city              = [[Wellesley, Massachusetts|Wellesley]]\n |state             = [[Massachusetts]]\n |country           = United States\n |coor              = {{Coord|42|17|53.63|N|71|15|40.29|W|type:edu|display=title}}\n |campus            = [[Suburb]]an <br> {{convert|350|acre|km2}}\n |former_names      = Babson Institute<br />(1919\u20131969)\n |free_label        = \n |free              = \n |sports            = 22 varsity sports\n |colors            = [[Green]] and [[white]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Logo / Brand Usage \u2013 Quick Reference guide OCTOBER 2013|url=http://www.babson.edu/offices-services/marketing/guidelines-templates/Documents/babson-brand-guidelines.pdf|publisher=Babson College|accessdate=26 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413023946/http://www.babson.edu/offices-services/marketing/guidelines-templates/Documents/babson-brand-guidelines.pdf|archive-date=April 13, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><br>{{Color box|#006644|border=darkgray}} {{Color box|white|border=darkgray}}\n |nickname          = Beavers\n |mascot            = Biz E. Beaver\n |athletics         = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]]\n |website           = {{URL|http://www.babson.edu/}}\n |logo              = File:Babson College logo.svg\n |footnotes         = \n}}\n\n'''Babson College''' is a [[private school|private]] [[business school]] in [[Wellesley, Massachusetts]]. Established in 1919, its central focus is on [[entrepreneurship education]]. It was founded by [[Roger Babson|Roger W. Babson]] as an [[Men's colleges in the United States|all-male]] business institute but is now coeducational.\n\n== History ==\n\n===20th century===\n\n====The Babson Institute====\nOn September 3, 1919, with an enrollment of twenty-seven students, the Babson Institute held its first classes in the former home of Roger and Grace Babson on Abbott Road in Wellesley Hills.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} [[Roger Babson]], the founder of the school, set out to distinguish the '''Babson Institute''' from colleges offering mainly instruction in business. The Institute provided intensive training in the fundamentals of production, [[finance]] and distribution in just one academic year, rather than four. The curriculum was divided into four subject areas: practical [[economics]], [[financial management]], business psychology and personal efficiency (which covered topics such as ethics, personal hygiene and interpersonal relationships). The program's pace assumed that students would learn arts and sciences content elsewhere.\n\nBabson favored a combination of class work and actual business training. Seasoned businessmen made up the majority of the faculty. To better prepare students for the realities of the business world, the Institute's curriculum focused more on practical experience and less on lectures. Students worked on group projects and class presentations, observed manufacturing processes during field trips to area factories and businesses, met with managers and executives, and viewed industrial films on Saturday mornings.\n\nThe institute also maintained a business environment as part of the students' everyday life. The students, required to wear professional attire, kept regular business hours (8:30&nbsp;a.m. to 5:00&nbsp;p.m., Monday through Friday and 8:30&nbsp;a.m. to noon on Saturday) and were monitored by punching in and out on a time clock. They were also assigned an office desk equipped with a telephone, typewriter, adding machine, and Dictaphone. Personal secretaries typed the students' assignments and correspondence in an effort to accurately reflect the business world. Roger Babson aimed to \"prepare his students to enter their chosen careers as executives, not anonymous members of the work force.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.babson.edu/About/History.cfm |title=Babson College: History |work=babson.edu |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228002014/http://www3.babson.edu/About/History.cfm |archivedate=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 1969, the Babson Institute's three-year bachelor of science in business administration, still for young men only, became a four-year bachelor of science degree, the Institute became a College and women were admitted for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babson.edu/about-babson/at-a-glance/babsons-history/timeline/Pages/default.aspx|title=Timeline \u2013 Babson History|first=Babson|last=College|website=www.babson.edu|accessdate=August 31, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170826071426/http://www.babson.edu/about-babson/at-a-glance/babsons-history/timeline/Pages/default.aspx|archive-date=August 26, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\n\n====Three College Collaboration====\nBabson is involved in a three college collaboration with [[Olin College]] and [[Wellesley College]] (a collaboration often referred to as BOW).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://centennial.babson.edu/babson100/|title=Babson 100|website=Babson Centennial|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bow3colleges.org/|title=Babson/Olin/Wellesley {{!}} Three College Collaboration|website=bow3colleges.org|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Wellesley Main Campus===\nThe main residential campus of Babson College is {{convert|350|acre|km2}} and located in the \"Babson Park\" section of [[Wellesley, Massachusetts]], just fifteen miles west of [[Boston]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babson.edu/About/ |title=About Babson |work=babson.edu |date=June 15, 2006 |accessdate=January 20, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101227181958/http://www3.babson.edu/About/| archivedate= December 27, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> It is adjacent to the [[Franklin W. Olin College of Engineering]]. Undergraduate and graduate students have the opportunity to take advantage of campus amenities including the student center, the cafeteria, Horn Library, multiple centers and institutes, the Webster fitness center, the Weissman Foundry the arts center, and a new centennial park known as the Kerry Murphy Healey Park. Executive and Enterprise Education visitors have the opportunity to stay in guest rooms adjacent to the meeting center.\n\n===Babson Boston===\nThe Babson Boston classroom and event space, located at 100 High Street, gives Babson a presence in downtown Boston and connects the resources of the College with the innovative companies, organizations and leaders in Boston's Financial District. Opened in 2016, this facility provides the opportunity to offer MBA courses in a location convenient to where entrepreneurial students live and work. Over the course of the academic year, there are opportunities at the Boston location for students to engage with Babson offices and resources, including graduate programs, the Graduate Center for Career Development, Graduate Admissions and the College's alumni network. From 2011 to 2016, Babson Boston campus was at 253 Summer Street in Boston's Innovation District.\n\n===Babson San Francisco===\nBabson has a San Francisco campus which includes a Blended Learning MBA program, an undergraduate semester experience and custom executive education.\n\n===Babson Miami===\nIn July 2017, President [[Kerry Healey]] announced Babson's plans to expand to [[Miami, Florida]], where the Blended Learning MBA, Master of Science in Business Analytics (MSBA) and Certificate in Advanced Management (CAM), three graduate programs are offered. Babson's new hub in Miami is located at 1200 Brickell Avenue.\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Undergraduate===\nBabson College offers all undergraduates a [[bachelor of science]] degree. Students are also given the option to declare concentrations their junior and senior year from a broad range of subjects in various business and other fields.  Programs are accredited by [[Association to Advance Collegiate Schools of Business]] (AACSB)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://datadirect.aacsb.edu/public/profiles/profile.cfm?runReport=1&unitid=54394&userType=All |title=AACSB: Accredited institutions |work=datadirect.aacsb.edu |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref> and the College itself has been regionally accredited by the [[New England Association of Schools and Colleges]] (NEASC) since 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cihe.neasc.org/about_our_institutions/roster_of_institutions/details/8136|title=NEASC CIHE: Babson College|publisher=|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBabson College also offers a study abroad they have created. The program is called \"BRIC: The Cornerstone of the New Global Economy\" and is offered to Juniors as well as Seniors in the fall semester of the academic year. During the program a number of students, around 26, visit and study in Russia, China and India. In each country, students study a variety of classes covering different topics.\n\n{{Infobox business school rankings\n| BWu = 26\n| USNWRu =\n| BWg =56\n| FT = 60\n| USNWRg = 65\n| BI = 40\n}}\nIn rankings, Babson was rated first among all colleges and universities in the nation by ''[[Money Magazine]]'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/money/collection/moneys-best-colleges/ |title=The Best Colleges for Your Money |magazine=Money |year=2014}}</ref> In 2015, the magazine ranked it second just behind [[Stanford University]].<ref name=\"MONEY's Best Colleges\">{{Cite web|title = MONEY's Best Colleges|url = https://best-colleges.time.com/money/full-ranking#/list|website = best-colleges.time.com|accessdate = 2015-07-14}}</ref> Babson's MBA program has been ranked number one in [[entrepreneurship]] for twenty-one consecutive years by ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Entrepreneurship \u2013 Best Business Schools|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-business-schools/entrepreneurship-rankings|accessdate=March 13, 2012|newspaper=U.S. News and World Report}}</ref> and is ranked 58th overall in the ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'' 2014 rankings.<ref>{{cite news|title=Full-Time MBA Programs|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bschools/rankings/|publisher=BloombergBusinessWeek|year=2014}}</ref> Babson's undergraduate business program is ranked 26th overall in the Bloomberg Businessweek 2014 rankings.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bschools/rankings#5 |title=Undergraduate Business School Programs=Businessweek |year=2014 |accessdate=21 August 2015 |work=Bloomberg}}</ref> Babson's undergraduate Entrepreneurship program has been ranked number one for the past 17 years by ''U.S. News & World Report.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/rankings/business-entrepreneurship |title=College Ranking Lists > Entrepreneurship Rankings |publisher=U.S. News & World Report : Colleges |date=2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> In their 2013\u20132014 salary report, [[Payscale.com]] ranked Babson College at number five of all U.S. colleges and universities, ahead of schools such as Stanford, University of Pennsylvania, Harvard, Dartmouth, Columbia and Yale. This ranking represents an average mid-career salary of $123,000 and average starting salary of $59,700.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.payscale.com/college-salary-report-2014/full-list-of-schools |title=Full List of Schools \u2013 PayScale College Salary Report 2013\u201314 |publisher=Payscale |date=2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112174459/http://www.payscale.com/college-salary-report-2014/full-list-of-schools |archive-date=November 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2012, ''Bloomberg Businessweek'' ranked Babson eleventh among U.S. schools based on return on investment. Babson is the highest ranking private business college. The others are either major universities or engineering schools.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2012-04-09/college-roi-what-we-found |first=Louis |last=Lavelle |title=College ROI: What We Found |magazine=Businessweek |date=9 April 2012 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> CNN money ranked Babson eighth in their 2016 \"Colleges with the highest-paid grads\" rankings.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://money.cnn.com/2016/09/20/pf/college/top-colleges-graduate-earnings/index.html | work=CNN | first=Katie | last=Lobosco | title=Colleges with the highest-paid graduates | date=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Graduate===\n\nBabson College offers master's degrees through its F. W. Olin Graduate School of Business, including a One-Year MBA Program, a Two-Year MBA Program, a 42-month Evening MBA Program and a Blended Learning MBA Program with campuses located in [[Boston]], [[San Francisco]] and [[Miami]]. It also offers a Master's of Science in Entrepreneurial Leadership (MSEL), Business Analytics (MSBA), Finance (MSF) and a Certificate of Advanced Management (CAM).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babson.edu/admission/graduate/Pages/default.aspx |title=Graduate Business Masters Degrees |publisher=Babson College |date=2016 |accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n[[File:Arthur M. Blank Center, Babson College - IMG 0388.JPG|thumb|right|Arthur M. Blank Center]]\n[[Image:Babsonglobe2008.jpg|thumb|right|The Babson Globe]]\nIn 2019, 3,663 students attended Babson, 3,229 of whom were [[undergraduate]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/babson-college-2121 |title=Babson College |publisher=U.S. News & World Report : Colleges |date=2014 |accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nStudent publications include a literary magazine<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www3.babson.edu/Students/Undergraduate/Organizations/litmag/default.cfm/ |title='&#39;Babson Literary Magazine'&#39; |work=babson.edu |date=June 15, 2006 |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718150356/http://www3.babson.edu/Students/Undergraduate/Organizations/litmag/default.cfm |archive-date=July 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and the Babson Built Podcast.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.babson.edu/entrepreneurship/2018/04/05/babson-built-podcast/ |title='&#39;Babson Built Podcast'&#39; |work=babson.edu |date=April 15, 2018 |accessdate=October 27, 2019 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere are several [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|fraternities and sororities]] on campus: [[Chi Omega]], [[Delta Tau Delta]], [[Kappa Kappa Gamma]], [[Sigma Kappa]] and [[Sigma Phi Epsilon]]. There are also two professional business fraternities on campus: [[Delta Sigma Pi]] and [[Alpha Kappa Psi]]. Babson College Radio was started in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cybertalk.com/030198.htm |title=www.cybertalk.com |date=March 1, 1998 |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708214753/http://www.cybertalk.com/030198.htm |archive-date=July 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nBabson offers a variety of special interest housing, such as CODE (Community of Developers and Entrepreneurs), theStudio (the housing associated with CREATE, the arts-based student club), E-Tower, ONE Tower: Origins of Necessary Equality, GIVE Tower, Healthy Living Tower and Women Giving Back Tower.\n\n==Athletics==\nBabson's teams are known as the \"Beavers\" and its colors are green and white. The school has 22 [[Varsity team|varsity sports teams]], the majority of which compete in the [[New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference]] (NEWMAC) of the [[NCAA Division III]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newmaconline.com/ |title=NEWMAC online |publisher=NEWMAC online |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208190434/http://www.newmaconline.com/ |archivedate=February 8, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> One of Babson's flagship sports is baseball which has won 7 Conference Championships and been to 5 NCAA Tournaments, including the 2019 College World Series. Additionally, the men's soccer team has established a history of success with 3 NCAA National Championships, 27 NCAA tournaments wins and 12 conference championships. The men's and women's alpine ski teams compete in the [[United States Collegiate Ski and Snowboard Association]] (USCSA)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uscsa.com/member-schools.html |title=Members |publisher=USCSA |accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> and the men's lacrosse team competes in the [[Pilgrim League]]. Babson College's men's hockey team competes in the [[Eastern College Athletic Conference]] (ECAC) and has won (1) NCAA D3 National title, (1) ECAC D2 title, six ECAC East Championships, appearing in the championship game in 9 of the last 12 seasons {{as of|2015|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.babsonathletics.com/sports/m-hockey/2014-15/releases/20150305uwatxs |title=CAC East Championship Preview: No. 10/12 Men's Ice Hockey at No. 1/2 Norwich |publisher=Babson Athletics |date= |accessdate=21 August 2015}}</ref> Babson College's golf team competes in the [[New England Collegiate Conference]] (NECC) and won the title in 2011 giving them an automatic bid to the NCAAs. They were led by senior captain Joe Young who won NECC golfer of the year in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://babsonathletics.com/sports/m-golf/index |title=Babson Athletics |publisher=Babson Athletics |date= |accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref> Babson United Rugby Club won Northeast region of NSCRO 7's in 2016. In 2017, the school will begin construction of the Babson Recreation and Athletics Center, a major new facility that will support varsity, intramural and recreational sports and many other activities by the fall of 2019. In March 2017, Babson's basketball team won the Division III National Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theswellesleyreport.com/2017/07/babson-has-huge-recreational-facility-overhaul-on-tap/|title=Babson has huge athletics/recreation facility overhaul on tap \u2013 The Swellesley Report - News about Wellesley, Massachusetts|website=theswellesleyreport.com|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Alumni==\n{{Alumni|date=December 2016}}\n<!-- ONLY ADD A NAME TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE A WIKIPEDIA ARTICLE-->\n\n===Business and athletics===\n* [[Ernesto Bertarelli]] '89: Swiss businessman\n* [[Arthur Blank|Arthur M. Blank]] '63 H'98: co-founder, former CEO of [[The Home Depot]]\n* [[Peter Boss]] MBA '10: race car driver\n* [[Edward Bronfman|Edward Maurice Bronfman]] '50 (1927\u20132005): businessman, founder of [[Edper Investments]]\n* [[Matt Chatham]] MBA '11: former NFL linebacker with the [[New England Patriots]]\n* [[Anthony Chiasson]] '95: hedge fund manager\n* [[Matt Coffin]] '90: founder and former President of [[LowerMyBills.com]]<ref>[http://www.babson.edu/Academics/centers/blank-center/alumni-entrepreneur-hall-of-fame/Pages/2009-Honorees.aspx \"2009 Honorees, Arthur M. Blank Center for Entrepreneurship\"], Babson.edu. Retrieved October 31, 2013</ref>\n* [[Andr\u00f3nico Luksic Craig]] '76: businessman\n* [[Bob Davis (businessman)|Bob Davis]] MBA '85: founder and CEO of [[Lycos]]\n* [[Edsel Ford II|Edsel Bryant Ford II]] '73 H'00: Board Director of the [[Ford Motor Company]]\n* [[William D. Green]] '76 MBA '77 H'07: Former Chairman and CEO of [[Accenture]]\n* [[Frederic C. Hamilton]] '48 H'98 MP'82 (1927\u20132016): oil pioneer\n* [[Peter Kellogg|Peter R. Kellogg]] '64: financial broker\n* [[Will Langhorne]] '95: former race car driver\n* [[Peter E. Madden]] '64 P'04 Honorary Trustee: former President of the [[State Street Corporation]]\n* [[Dean Metropoulos|Charles Dean Metropoulos]] '67 MBA '68: co-owner of [[Hostess Brands]] and former owner of [[Pabst Brewing Company]] \n* [[Geoff Molson|Geoffrey Eric Molson]] MBA '96: co-owner, President and CEO of the [[Montreal Canadiens]]\n* [[David G. Mugar]] '62: businessperson\n* [[Gunnar S. Overstrom Jr.]] '65 (1942\u20132001): former Vice Chairman of [[FleetBoston Financial]]\n* [[Aly Raisman]] Olympic gold medalist for [[United States women's national gymnastics team]]\n* [[Scott Sharp]] '90: race car driver\n* [[Jamie Siminoff]] '99: businessperson\n* [[Jacob Sprague]] '07: rugby player\n* [[Akio Toyoda]] MBA '82 MP' 14: President and CEO of [[Toyota Motor Corporation]]\n\n===Food and entertainment===\n* [[Marc Bell (entrepreneur)|Marc Bell]] '89: entrepreneur\n* [[Terrell Braly]] '77: founder of [[Quiznos]]\n* [[Gustavo Cisneros]] '68 H'19: President/CEO of [[Grupo Cisneros|Organizacion Diego Cisneros]]\n* [[Roger Enrico]] '65 H'86 (1994\u20132016): former CEO of [[PepsiCo]] and [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] Animation SKG <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.referenceforbusiness.com/biography/A-E/Enrico-Roger-1944.html |title=Roger Enrico 1944\u2014 Biography \u2013 Two early lessons, Enters the cola wars, Turns attention to foods and restaurants |publisher=Referenceforbusiness.com |date= |accessdate=January 20, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Stephen Gaghan]] '88: screenwriter\n* [[Daniel Frank Gerber]] '20 H'67 (1898\u20131974): founder of [[Gerber Products Company]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hbs.edu/leadership/20th-century-leaders/Pages/details.aspx?profile=daniel_f_gerber_jr |title=Great American Business Leaders of the 20th Century |publisher=Harvard Business School |date=January 19, 2018 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Bernard Lee (poker player)|Bernard Lee]] MBA '99: professional poker player<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://harvardmagazine.com/2012/11/the-busiest-man-in-poker |title=The Busiest Man in Poker |magazine=Harvard Magazine |date=November\u2013December 2012 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[John LeFevre]] '01: former Citibank banker\n* [[Mir Ibrahim Rahman]] '00: CEO of [[GEO TV]]<ref>http://www.geo.tv/anniversary/1st/english/page4.htm  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040412225608/http://www.geo.tv/anniversary/1st/english/page4.htm |date=April 12, 2004 }}</ref>\n*[[Nelson Woss]] '91: Australian film producer of ''[[Ned Kelly (2003 film)|Ned Kelly]]'' & ''[[Red Dog (film)|Red Dog]]''\n{{colend}}\n\n===Government, education, and other===\n* [[Craig Benson|Craig Robert Benson]] '77, businessperson, former Governor of New Hampshire\n* [[Vincent E. Boles]] MBA '88: Major General US Army \n* [[W. Haydon Burns]] '34 (1912\u20131987): 35th [[Governor of Florida]], 1965\u201367 and 35th Mayor of [[Jacksonville, Florida]], 1949\u20131965<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dos.myflorida.com/florida-facts/florida-history/florida-governors/william-haydon-burns/ |title=William Haydon Burns |publisher=Florida Department of State |date=|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Princess Marie of Denmark]]: attended 1995-97<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kongehuset.dk/en/the-royal-house/prince-joachim-and-princess-marie/hrh-princess-marie |title=HRH Princess Marie |publisher=The Danish Monarchy |date=|accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Rudy Crew]] '72 H'96: President of [[Medgar Evers College]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/25/education/new-leader-is-named-for-medgar-evers-college.html |title=New Leader Is Named for Medgar Evers College |newspaper=New York Times |date=June 24, 2013 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Kathleen M. Gainey]] MBA '89: lieutenant general US Army<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.army.mil/article/8022/gainey_confirmed_by_senate_for_third_star |title=Gainey confirmed by Senate for third star |publisher=U.S. Army News Release |date=March 20, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[James A. Lewis]] '58 (1932\u20131997): American politician\n* [[Patricia E. McQuistion]] MBA '88: lieutenant general US Army<ref>{{cite news|url=http://qconline.com/news/local/first-female-senior-commander-returns-to-arsenal-for-women-s/article_ada0a4e3-c0b7-53c9-9465-859f56573442.html |title=First female senior commander returns to Arsenal for Women's Equality Day speech |publisher=The Dispatch\u2013Argus |date=September 4, 2016 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lafayette Morgan]] '58 (1931\u20132005): former Economic Advisor of Liberia<ref>{{cite news |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200504290902.html |title=Liberia: Former Economic Advisor in Liberia, Lafayette Morgan Dies At 74 |publisher=Liberian Observer |date=April 29, 2005 |accessdate=February 8, 2018 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20121013204409/http://allafrica.com/stories/200504290902.html |archivedate=October 13, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Ernest Dichmann Peek]] '29 (1878\u20131950): major general, U.S. Army\n* [[Gustavo Adolfo Carvajal Sinisterra]] MBA '84: the 24th Ambassador of Colombia to France<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elpais.com.co/economia/ocde-traera-grandes-oportunidades-embajador-de-colombia-en-francia.html |title=Ocde traer\u00e1 grandes oportunidades embajador de Colombia en Francia |newspaper=El Pa\u00eds |date=June 2, 2013 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Don Strauch]] '49 (1926\u20132016): former Mayor of [[Mesa, Arizona]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/mesa/contributor/2016/02/04/mesa-history-remembering-mayor-don-strauch/79446386/ |title=Mesa history: Remembering Mayor Don Strauch |publisher=AZCentral USA Today |date=February 4, 2016 |accessdate=February 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Tilton]] (1951\u20132017) '74 P'09: art dealer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/10/arts/design/jack-tilton-dead-manhattan-gallery-owner.html|title=Jack Tilton, Art Dealer With an Eye for the New, Dies at 66|first=William|last=Grimes|date=May 10, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=August 31, 2017|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n===Fashion and fitness===\n* [[Michael Bastian]] '87: founder of American menswear firm MICHAEL BASTIAN whose majority stake was acquired in 2016 by brand management firm Bluestar Alliance LLC whose annual brand retail sales exceed $3 billion<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bluestaralliance.com/bluestar-alliance-buys-majority-stake-in-michael-bastian/ |title=Bluestar Alliance Buys Majority Stake in Michael Bastian |publisher=Bluestar Alliance |date=January 7, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/media/babson/site-assets/content-assets/about/events/babson-magazine/summer-2011/winter-2011/Feature-Fashion.pdf |title=They Got the Look |publisher=Babson College |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Enrico Marone Cinzano|Count Enrico Marone Cinzano]] '85: artist, furniture designer<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/yjeanmundelsalle/2016/06/13/italian-designer-enrico-marone-cinzano-creates-furniture-with-a-conscience/ |title=Italian Designer Enrico Marone Cinzano Creates Furniture With A Conscience |magazine=Forbes Magazine |date=June 13, 2016 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> and member of Italy's prominent [[Cinzano]] liquor family<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-10-31-mn-5-story.html|title=Count Alberto Marone Cinzano; Chairman of Vermouth Firm |publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=October 31, 1989|access-date=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Ruthie Davis]] MBA '93: founder, President and designer of the fashion and footwear firm RUTHIE DAVIS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.babson.edu/about/entrepreneurs-of-all-kinds/profiles/ruthie-davis.php |title=Profiles Ruthie Davis MBA'93 |publisher=Babson College |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ruthiedavis.com/about/ |title=About Ruthie Davis |publisher=Ruthie Davis |date= |accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Natasha Esch]] '93: former President of [[Wilhelmina Models]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1993/03/10/a-successful-pose/33199152-d69e-4cd0-b139-961685fd6671/ |title=A Successful Pose |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 10, 1993 |accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Mohan Murjani]] '67: as Chairman of the Murjani Group Murjani developed, launched and built [[Tommy Hilfiger (company)]] as well as [[Gloria Vanderbilt]] fashion empires<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/26/style/26iht-luxury08-Murjani.18176690.html |title=Mohan Murjani, chairman, Murjani Group |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 26, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Alberto Perlman]] '98: co-founder of Zumba Fitness\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Babson College}}\n* [http://www.babson.edu/ Official website]\n* [http://www.babsonathletics.com/ Official athletics website]\n\n{{New England Women's and Men's Athletic Conference navbox}}\n{{New England Hockey Conference}}\n{{New England Collegiate Conference}}\n{{AICUM}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Babson College|*]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1919]]\n[[Category:Wellesley, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Norfolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1919 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:New England Hockey Conference teams]]\n", "name_user": "ElKevbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUndergraduate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Babson_College"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Saskatchewan}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Saskatchewan]], [[Canada]]\n| first_outbreak  = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| index_case      = [[Saskatoon]]\n| arrival_date    = March 9, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=9|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| confirmed_cases = 300\n| active_cases    = 118\n| recovery_cases  = 178\n| deaths          = 4\n| website         = {{URL|https://www.saskatchewan.ca/COVID19}}\n| map1            = Saskatchewan COVID-19 Infection Rates.svg\n| map1_size       = 200px\n| map1_upright    = 1\n| alt1            = Map of COVID-19 infection density by region.\n| legend1         = Total cases by region, per 100,000 residents (2018 population estimate):\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}{{legend|#900000|>40}}{{legend|#c80200|>30}}\n{{col-break}}{{legend|#ee7070|>20}}{{legend|#ffc0c0|>10}}\n{{col-break}}{{legend|#ffdfe0|>0}}{{legend|#e0e0e0|0}}\n{{col-end}}\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan''' is an [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). {{As of|2020|04|12|df=US}}, 19,276 tests have been conducted, with 296 confirmed and 2 presumptive cases, 164 recoveries, and 4 deaths in [[Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\"saskcovid19\">{{cite web |url=https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/health-care-administration-and-provider-resources/treatment-procedures-and-guidelines/emerging-public-health-issues/2019-novel-coronavirus/cases-and-risk-of-covid-19-in-saskatchewan |title=Cases and Risk of COVID-19 in Saskatchewan (updated daily) |website=Government of Saskatchewan}}</ref> While a number of cases are still under investigation, 129 cases have been linked to travel, 112 have been the result of contact/community gatherings with other COVID-19 victims, and 25 cases have been from unidentified local exposures.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2020/april/12/covid-19-update-april-12 |title=COVID-19 Update |date=April 12, 2020 |website=Government of Saskatchewan}}</ref>{{clarify|date=April 2020|reason=The authorities have not stated whether the travel cases include domestic travel in addition to international travel, nor have they stated whether the mass gatherings include out-of-province events such as the Edmonton curling tournament or the Vancouver dental conference.}} The area of [[Saskatoon]] has seen the most reported cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ckom.com/2020/04/07/hold-april-7/|title=25 health-care workers among Sask. COVID-19 cases|date=|website=650 CKOM|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>  The coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan is part of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada]].\n\n==Timeline==\nSaskatchewan's Chief Medical Officer Saqib Shahab announced the first presumptive case of in the province on March 12, a person in their 60s that had recently returned from [[Egypt]], who was tested on March 9, and was in self-isolation at their home.<ref name=\"first\">{{cite news |last1=Giles |first1=David |title=Saskatchewan confirms first presumptive case of novel coronavirus |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6666466/coronavirus-saskatchewan-covid-19-coronavirus-saskatoon/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> By March 16, the number of presumptive cases in the province had increased to seven.<ref name=\"cases316\">{{cite news |last1=Giles |first1=David |title=Saskatchewan reports 7th presumptive case of coronavirus |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6685561/confirmed-presumptive-cases-covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317145935/https://globalnews.ca/news/6685561/confirmed-presumptive-cases-covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus/ |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 17, one new case was reported.<ref name=\"case317\">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Austin |title=COVID-19: Sask. records eighth case of coronavirus |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-17/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Regina Leader-Post |publisher=Postmedia |date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319184303/https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-17/ |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day, the College of Dental Surgeons of Saskatchewan recommended that those who attended the 2020 Pacific Dental Conference in [[Vancouver]] to self-isolate after many cases, including two in Saskatchewan, were linked to the event.<ref name=\"dentistemergency\">{{cite news |last1=Warick |first1=Jason |title=Sask. dentists asked to consider limiting work to emergencies only |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/dentists-asked-emergency-work-only-1.5501058 |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=CBC News |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319123046/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/dentists-asked-emergency-work-only-1.5501058 |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nOn March 18, 8 new cases were reported.<ref name=\"emergency\">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Austin |title=Sask. declares state of emergency after eight new coronavirus cases |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-18/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Regina Leader-Post |publisher=Postmedia |date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319183516/https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-18/ |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 19, four new cases were reported, bringing the provincial total to 20.<ref name=\"cases319\">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Austin |title=COVID-19: Sask. reports four new coronavirus cases, bringing total to 20 |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-19/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Regina Leader-Post |publisher=Postmedia |date=March 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320164217/https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-03-19/ |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 20, six new cases were reported, and 8 were confirmed.<ref name=\"cases320\">{{cite news |last1=Guignard |first1=Jonathan |title=Number of COVID-19 cases in Saskatchewan rises to 26, 8 confirmed |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6708930/coronavirus-saskstachewan-government-to-provide-update/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321141136/https://globalnews.ca/news/6708930/coronavirus-saskstachewan-government-to-provide-update/ |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 21, 2020, 18 new cases were reported,<ref name=\"cases321\">{{cite news |last1=Djuric |first1=Mickey |title=Coronavirus: Saskatchewan reports 18 new COVID-19 cases, province totals 44 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6713523/coronavirus-saskatchewan-new-cases/ |accessdate=March 23, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 21, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322131901/https://globalnews.ca/news/6713523/coronavirus-saskatchewan-new-cases/ |archive-date=March 22, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> including 11 healthcare workers who attended a physicians' bonspiel at a curling club in [[Edmonton]] on the week of March 11.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/11-sask-healthcare-workers-test-positive-for-covid-19-after-curling-bonspiel-in-alta-1.4862909|title=11 Sask. healthcare workers test positive for COVID-19 after curling bonspiel in Alta.|date=2020-03-21|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323063048/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/11-sask-healthcare-workers-test-positive-for-covid-19-after-curling-bonspiel-in-alta-1.4862909|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 22, 8 more cases were reported.<ref name=\"cases 322\">{{cite news |last1=Solomon |first1=Michaela |title=8 new cases of COVID-19 in Sask., total at 52 |url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/8-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-sask-total-at-52-1.4863521 |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=CTV News |publisher=Bell Media |date=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323164841/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/8-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-sask-total-at-52-1.4863521 |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nOn March 23, 14 new cases were reported, and only one was still presumptive.<ref name=\"cases323\">{{cite news |last1=Guignard |first1=Jonathan |title=Coronavirus: Saskatchewan reports 14 new COVID-19 cases, bringing total to 66 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6719062/coronavirus-saskatchewan-to-provide-update-on-covid-19-pandemic/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323231240/https://globalnews.ca/news/6719062/coronavirus-saskatchewan-to-provide-update-on-covid-19-pandemic/ |archive-date=March 23, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> On March 24, six new confirmed cases were reported, totalling 72 confirmed cases. This includes four cases thought to possibly be the result of community transmission, pending a full investigation.<ref name=\"cases324\">{{cite news |last1=Piller |first1=Thomas |title=Coronavirus: Saskatchewan reports 6 new COVID-19 cases, bringing total to 72 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6726305/coronavirus-saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-24/ |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 24, 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325130857/https://globalnews.ca/news/6726305/coronavirus-saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-24/ |archive-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another new 14 cases were announced on March 25. On March 26 and 27, 9 new cases were reported each.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6743122/covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus-march-27/|title=9 new coronavirus cases reported in Saskatchewan; PPE goes missing from health authority|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327232129/https://globalnews.ca/news/6743122/covid-19-saskatchewan-coronavirus-march-27/|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cases326\">{{cite news |last1=Giles |first1=David |title=Coronavirus: 9 new COVID-19 cases reported in Saskatchewan, total rises to 95 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6738102/coronavirus-covid-19-saskatchewan-march-26/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=Global News |publisher=Corus Entertainment |date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327034843/https://globalnews.ca/news/6738102/coronavirus-covid-19-saskatchewan-march-26/ |archive-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, Saskatchewan announced the largest single-day increase in cases, at 30. The spike, especially in northern and central Saskatchewan, was attributed to 18 cases involving attendees of a snowmobile rally in [[Christopher Lake]] on March 14.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6746486/saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-28/|title=Saskatchewan sees biggest jump in COVID-19 cases, 30 reported Saturday|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329022053/https://globalnews.ca/news/6746486/saskatchewan-covid-19-cases-march-28/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/30-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-sask-6-people-in-hospital-1.4872587|title=30 new cases of COVID-19 in Sask., 6 people in hospital|last=|first=|date=2020-03-28|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329001244/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/30-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-sask-6-people-in-hospital-1.4872587|archive-date=March 29, 2020|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> The [[Saskatchewan Health Authority]] (SHA) initially announced two positive cases (including a participant, and a server at an associated dinner) on March 25, and has advised self-isolation for anyone who had attended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/two-people-who-attended-christopher-lake-snowmobile-rally-test-positive-for-covid-19-sha-1.4868716|title=Two people who attended Christopher Lake snowmobile rally test positive for COVID-19: SHA|last=|first=|date=2020-03-25|website=CTV News Saskatoon|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326165207/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/two-people-who-attended-christopher-lake-snowmobile-rally-test-positive-for-covid-19-sha-1.4868716|archive-date=March 26, 2020|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-people-1.4867855|title=14 new COVID-19 cases in Sask. as province limits gatherings to 10 people|date=2020-03-25|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326165208/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-people-1.4867855|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOn March 30, the confirmed case count rose to 176, and Saskatchewan also reported its first deaths from COVID-19. Both people were in their 70s and were from separate parts of the province.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/coronavirus-saskatchewan-1.5514563 |title=COVID-19 in Sask: Province marks 'sad milestone' of first 2 deaths |last1=Quenneville |first1=Guy |last2=Hunter |first2=Adam |work=[[CBC News]] |date=2020-03-30 |access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBy April 6, Saskatchewan had 253 cases and 81 recoveries. For the first time, the number of new recoveries (14) exceeded the number of new cases (4).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/4-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-province-encourages-downloading-saskalert-app-1.4884205|title=4 new COVID-19 cases in Sask., province encourages downloading SaskAlert app|date=2020-04-06|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Seven new cases and recoveries were announced the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/saskatchewan-reaches-260-covid-19-cases-7-new-recoveries-1.4886679|title=Saskatchewan reaches 260 COVID-19 cases, 7 new recoveries|date=2020-04-07|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>  The total number of cases continued to rise, reaching 289 on April 11, though the remaining active cases fell to 138 \u2014 dropping for the first time below the number of recoveries (which rose to 147).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/sask-now-has-more-covid-19-recoveries-than-active-cases-1.4892399 |title=Sask. now has more COVID-19 recoveries than active cases |publisher=CTV News Regina |date=April 11, 2020 |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Image frame\n |caption = COVID-19 Cases in Saskatchewan<ref name=saskcovid19 />\n |pos = top\n |align = center\n |border = no\n |content = {{Gallery layout\n  |content = {{gallery layout content\n   |content = {{Graph:Ch