{{cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/gatherings-of-250-people-or-more-banned-in-sask-as-second-presumptive-covid-19-case-confirmed-1.4852364|title=Gatherings of 250 people or more banned in Sask. as second presumptive COVID-19 case confirmed|date=March 13, 2020|website=CTV News Saskatoon|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313211404/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/gatherings-of-250-people-or-more-banned-in-sask-as-second-presumptive-covid-19-case-confirmed-1.4852364|archive-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Exceptions are permitted for retail shops.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6684078/hospitals-casinos-coronavirus-prevention-saskatchewan/|title=Hospital visitor restrictions, casinos closing part of coronavirus prevention|website=Global News|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name = Sask-update-March13>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/province-increased-measures-covid-19-update-1.5497233 |title=\"Saskatchewan officials provide COVID update after second presumptive casecfound in province\", CBC News, March 13, 2020. |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314132339/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/province-increased-measures-covid-19-update-1.5497233 |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> An exception for faith-based organizations was removed March 16.<ref name=\":0\" /> The government sharply reduced inter-provincial and international travel by any provincial employees on government business. It also provided that provincial employees who have travelled outside the country, whether on government business or personal travel, must self-isolate for 14 days upon their return.<ref name=\"Sask-update-March13\" />\n\nOn March 17, 2020, the government announced that it was delaying the introduction of the provincial budget, because the government revenue forecasts underlying it were no longer reliable, in light of the current situation.  The Government would announce the planned spending, including for the health care sector, which would see an increase in funding.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/sask-gov-budget-postponed-1.5500607 |title=\"Sask. government postpones full budget, will release spending plans Wednesday\", Adam Hunter, CBC News, March 17, 2020. |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321175144/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/sask-gov-budget-postponed-1.5500607 |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The same day, the Legislature passed amendments to provincial employment law, to provide unpaid job security to employees during the pandemic.  The amendments passed with the support of both parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-introduces-unpaid-job-protected-leave-1.4856960|title=COVID-19: Sask. introduces unpaid job protected leave|first=Michaela|last=Solomon|date=March 17, 2020|website=CTV News|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327064802/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-introduces-unpaid-job-protected-leave-1.4856960|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, the Legislature adjourned its spring sitting, with the consent of the Opposition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/legislature-adjourned-1.5503813 |title=\"Saskatchewan legislative sitting abruptly adjourned amid COVID-19 pandemic\", Adam Hunter, CBC News, March 19, 2020. |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321144331/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/legislature-adjourned-1.5503813 |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===State of emergency===\nSaskatchewan declared a state of emergency on March 18, which included a ban of all gatherings of 50 people or more, restricting capacity of restaurants and similar venues to a maximum of 50 or half their normal capacity (whichever was lower), mandatory closure of all fitness facilities, casinos, and bingo halls, shifting all provincial government entities and crown corporations to remote work on March 23, authorizing the [[Saskatchewan Health Authority]] to \"redeploy nurses and other staff and ensure medical supplies and personal protective equipment are available when needed and reduce risk of further exposure to our care providers and patients\", and advising against non-essential travel outside of the province.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-declares-state-of-emergency-additional-measures-after-announcing-8-new-cases-1.4858436|title=COVID-19: Sask. declares state of emergency, additional measures, after announcing 8 new cases|date=March 18, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|access-date=March 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319004333/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-declares-state-of-emergency-additional-measures-after-announcing-8-new-cases-1.4858436|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cjme.com/2020/03/14/new-restrictions-announced-as-sask-covid-19-cases-rise-to-6/|title=New restrictions announced as Sask. COVID-19 cases rise to 6|website=[[CJME|980 CJME]]|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6698018/saskatchewan-state-of-emergency-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Saskatchewan declares state of emergency as coronavirus concerns grow|website=Global News|access-date=March 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318221045/https://globalnews.ca/news/6698018/saskatchewan-state-of-emergency-covid-19-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOn March 20, Premier Moe signed an order allowing regulations issued pursuant to the state of emergency, whether by the government or the chief medical officer, to be enforceable under provincial law. Law enforcement agencies, including the [[RCMP]], were granted the authority to enforce these measures under penalties of fines or arrest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6710474/saskatchewan-order-enforcing-measures-protecting-against-covid-19/|title=Saskatchewan premier signs order enforcing measures protecting against spread of COVID-19|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321135259/https://globalnews.ca/news/6710474/saskatchewan-order-enforcing-measures-protecting-against-covid-19/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The government subsequently announced that residents returning from any international travel, those who have tested positive,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6787934/regina-police-ticket-public-health-order-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Woman ticketed for violating public health order tests positive for COVID-19: Regina police|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> and those identified as recent contacts of someone who had tested positive, would be required by law to self-isolate for 14 days, with those breaking quarantine subject to a $2,000 fine.<ref name=\":10\" /> Essential travellers such as working crews, transport workers and health care workers were exempt.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/mandatory-self-isolation-after-travel-now-law-as-sask-announces-6-more-covid-19-cases-1.4861706|title=Mandatory self-isolation after travel now law as Sask. announces 6 more COVID-19 cases|date=March 20, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320224446/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/mandatory-self-isolation-after-travel-now-law-as-sask-announces-6-more-covid-19-cases-1.4861706|archive-date=March 20, 2020 |}}</ref> Premier Moe cited concerns over those not following its previous self-isolation recommendations as justification for the legal measure;<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/this-is-now-the-law-here-are-the-new-measures-announced-in-sask-1.4861951|title='This is now the law': Here are the new measures announced in Sask.|last=|first=|date=2020-03-20|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321141614/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/this-is-now-the-law-here-are-the-new-measures-announced-in-sask-1.4861951|archive-date=March 21, 2020|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> indeed, on April 6, a COVID-19-infected individual who had violated the mandatory self-isolation order received the first fine under the new legal measure, issued by the [[Regina Police Service]] in the amount of {{Currency|2800|CAD}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://leaderpost.com/news/local-news/regina-woman-issued-2800-ticket-for-allegedly-violating-public-health-order/ |title=Regina woman issued $2,800 ticket for violating public health order |website=Regina Leader-Post |date=April 8, 2020 |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAdditional restrictions were also announced on March 20, to take effect on March 23.  All restaurants, bars, and nightclubs were restricted to take-out service only (bars and nightclubs could only do so if customers were capable of maintaining a distance of 2 metres from each other). All art galleries, museums, and other recreational, entertainment, and personal service facilities were ordered closed, and certain types of medical clinics (chiropractors, dentists, optometrists, [[Podiatrist|podiatrists]], and registered massage therapists) were restricted to non-elective appointments only. All gatherings of 25 people or more were prohibited unless all patrons were capable of maintaining a distance of 2 metres from each other.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatchewan-coronavirus-1.5504240|title=COVID-19 in Sask: Premier threatens international travellers who don't self-isolate with arrest, fines|last=Quenneville|first=Guy|date=March 20, 2020|website=|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321143011/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatchewan-coronavirus-1.5504240|archive-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 25, Saskatchewan announced that beginning March 26, all gatherings must be limited to 10 people, and all businesses not considered essential by the province were required to close to the public.  Examples of \"non-allowable business services\" included but were not limited to ATV, boat, and snowmobile retailers, clothing, shoe, accessory, and jewellery stores, electronics, entertainment, and toy stores, flower shops, book, gift, and stationary stores, sporting goods stores, pawn shops, and travel agencies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-1.4867855|title=14 new COVID-19 cases in Sask. as province limits gatherings to 10|date=2020-03-25|website=Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205555/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-1.4867855|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2020/march/25/allowable-business-services|title=Government Clarifies Allowable Business Services, Limits Gatherings To 10 Person Maximum|website=Government of Saskatchewan|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205555/https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2020/march/25/allowable-business-services|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Alert Ready]] has been activated several times to provide notice of the self-isolation order, first on March 20,<ref name=\":10\" /> and again March 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.620ckrm.com/2020/03/27/emergency-alert-issued-by-province-of-saskatchewan-due-to-covid-19/|title=Emergency alert for travelers issued by province of Saskatchewan due to COVID-19|last=McNally|first=Ryan|date=|website=620 CKRM|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n== Local responses ==\nOn March 18, a Sangster's health store in [[Lawson Heights, Saskatoon]] was closed after multiple visits by a customer who stated that she had recently returned from international travel to [[Hawaii]], and that multiple passengers on the flight had felt ill. The store's local owner criticized the customer for breaking recommended self-quarantine, even though she had displayed no symptoms herself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-after-brush-with-irresponsible-customer-saskatoon-business-closes-to-in-person-traffic-1.4859725|title=COVID-19: After brush with 'irresponsible' customer Saskatoon business closes to in-person traffic|last=Lynn|first=Josh|date=2020-03-19|website=Saskatoon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324195922/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-after-brush-with-irresponsible-customer-saskatoon-business-closes-to-in-person-traffic-1.4859725|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, [[Regina Transit]] and [[Saskatoon Transit]] suspended fares for all bus service, but with reduced service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-saskatoon-transit-for-essential-travel-only-city-says-1.4865940|title=COVID-19: Saskatoon Transit for 'essential travel only' city says|last=Lynn|first=Josh|date=2020-03-24|website=Saskatoon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160337/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-saskatoon-transit-for-essential-travel-only-city-says-1.4865940|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6701505/saskatoon-city-council-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Saskatoon city council passes special measures to deal with COVID-19 pandemic|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324195920/https://globalnews.ca/news/6701505/saskatoon-city-council-covid-19-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjme.com/2020/03/20/628329/|title=Regina Transit to keep operating, but with changes|date=|website=980 CJME|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nIn early April, Restaurants Canada, an industry organisation, announced that 25,000 restaurant jobs have been lost in Saskatchewan since March 1.  It also reported that approximately 10% of restaurants in Canada have closed permanently, and estimated that another 18% would close if the situation has not changed in a month's time.  Local restaurant operators expressed concerns whether they would be able to re-open.<ref>[https://leaderpost.com/news/local-news/saskatchewan-restaurant-industry-sees-25k-jobs-lost-due-to-covid-19/ \"Saskatchewan restaurant industry sees 25K jobs lost due to COVID-19\"], Mark Melnychuk< ''Regina Leader-Post'', April 3, 2020.</ref>\n\n=== Municipal orders with measures contrary to provincial measures ===\nThe municipal governments of [[Gravelbourg]] and Regina declared their own states of emergency with stricter restrictions than those enforced by the province. Regina announced an intent to ban all public meetings larger than 5 people or more (outside of home, workplaces, or as part of essential services), and order the closure of retail stores in specific categories to in-person shopping (including clothing, furniture, games, sporting goods, and toys) effective March 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6708095/regina-state-of-emergency/|title=Regina declares local state of emergency, limiting size of gatherings|website=Global News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322203551/https://globalnews.ca/news/6708095/regina-state-of-emergency/|archive-date=March 22, 2020|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>  Gravelbourg similarly ordered that all businesses be closed to the public for 14 days (delivery and curbside pickup would still be allowed, and there were special operating requirements planned for the local [[Federated Co-operatives|Co-op]] store), and that only a maximum of five employees could be in a building at any one time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-what-the-state-of-local-emergency-in-gravelbourg-sask-means-for-residents-1.4863507|title=Here's what the state of local emergency in Gravelbourg, Sask. means for residents|last=|first=|date=2020-03-22|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135828/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-what-the-state-of-local-emergency-in-gravelbourg-sask-means-for-residents-1.4863507|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Mayor of Regina [[Michael Fougere]] argued that Saskatchewan's initial restrictions were not strict enough, arguing that meetings of 50 people were too large to avoid possible community transmission, and that restaurants and bars should have been ordered to close rather than limit capacity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-mayor-of-regina-calling-for-even-stricter-regulations-1.4859506|title=COVID-19: Mayor of Regina calling for even stricter regulations|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 22, the province stated that it would take steps to ensure that its emergency measures maintain precedence over municipal orders that include \"contrary standards\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6716266/coronavirus-saskatchewan-municipalities-regulations/|title=Saskatchewan municipalities can\u2019t make up their own coronavirus regulations: province|website=Global News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135247/https://globalnews.ca/news/6716266/coronavirus-saskatchewan-municipalities-regulations/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Minister of Government Relations Lori Carr explained that \"during this time of great uncertainty, it is of the utmost importance that we provide certainty to Saskatchewan residents and make every effort to minimize confusion\", and cited Regina's attempts to close retail stores as an example of a restriction where provincial decisions take precedence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-some-clarification-on-the-conflicting-orders-made-by-the-province-and-the-city-of-regina-1.4863546|title=Here's some clarification on the conflicting orders made by the province and the City of Regina|date=2020-03-22|website=Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135124/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-some-clarification-on-the-conflicting-orders-made-by-the-province-and-the-city-of-regina-1.4863546|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/government-clarity-cregina-emergency-order-1.5506234|title=Government to review, cancel City of Regina emergency order|last=Eneas|first=Brian|date=2020-03-22|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151142/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/government-clarity-cregina-emergency-order-1.5506234|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Regional distribution==\n\n{{Annotated image\n |float=right\n |image-width=225\n |width=225\n |height=400\n |image=Saskatchewan COVID-19 Reporting Regions.svg{{!}}lang=en\n |annot-color=RoyalBlue\n |annot-text-align=center\n |annotations=\n  {{Annotation |109|33|  [[Black Lake, Saskatchewan|\u25cf]] }}\n  {{Annotation  |57|137| [[Buffalo Narrows, Saskatchewa