                  ||  10 || 0 || 0 ||   6 || 1\n|-\n|{{Left}} [[Saskatoon Health Region|Saskatoon]]      || 147 || 6 || 0 ||  78 || 1\n|-\n|{{Left}} South                                      ||  15 || 0 || 0 ||   6 || 0\n|-\n|{{Left}} [[Regina Qu'Appelle Health Region|Regina]] ||  63 || 1 || 0 ||  36 || 1\n|-class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"font-weight:bold;\"\n|{{Left}} Total                                      || 298 || 7 || 0 || 164 || 4\n|-class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"text-align:initial;\"\n|colspan=\"6\"| {{notelist|group=DistributionTableNotes}}\n|}\n\nThe regions are defined as follows:<ref name=\"saskcovid19\" />\n\n;Far North: The region administered by the Athabasca Health Authority, and the former Keewatin Yatth\u00e9 and Mamawetan Churchill River Health Regions.\n;North: The former [[Prairie North Health Region|Prairie North]], Prince Albert Parkland, and Kelsey Trail Health Regions.\n;Central: The former Heartland and Sunrise Health Regions.\n;Saskatoon: The former [[Saskatoon Health Region]].\n;South: The former Cypress, Five Hills, and Sun Country Health Regions.\n;Regina: The former [[Regina Qu'Appelle Health Region]].\n\n==School closures==\nThe [[University of Regina]] and [[University of Saskatchewan]] voluntarily suspended in-person classes on March 16, and switched to online courses for the remainder of the semester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/university-of-regina-suspends-classes-amid-covid-19-concerns-1.4852655|title=University of Regina suspends classes amid COVID-19 concerns|last=Ellis|first=Brendan|date=March 13, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314225820/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/university-of-regina-suspends-classes-amid-covid-19-concerns-1.4852655|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-concerns-prompt-u-of-s-to-temporarily-suspend-class-will-move-courses-online-1.4852879|title=COVID-19 concerns prompt U of S to temporarily suspend class, will move courses online|date=March 13, 2020|website=CTV News Saskatoon|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133901/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-concerns-prompt-u-of-s-to-temporarily-suspend-class-will-move-courses-online-1.4852879|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 16, the province announced that all public schools would \"wind down\" over the week, and close indefinitely on March 20. No academic penalties would be  issued for students that do not attend school during the week of March 20, final grades will be issued based on existing progress, and eligible Grade 12 students will be able to graduate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/sask-schools-closing-effective-march-20-over-covid-19-concerns-1.4854588|title=Sask. schools closing effective March 20 over COVID-19 concerns|date=March 16, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|url-status=live|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6683648/schools-saskatchewan-closing-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Public schools in Saskatchewan closing amid coronavirus concerns|website=Global News|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>  Day cares have been capped at 8 children per teacher.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada by province or territory|Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Saskatchewan|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Canada|coronavirus pandemic in Saskatchewan]]\n", "name_user": "Alejjx", "label": "safe", "comment": "daily update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Saskatchewan"}
